Once it is determined we are operating the instrument properly and it is still having an issue it is time for a swap. This is how it works with instruments from other manufacturer's that are on a swap basis. In this case we went through 3 rounds of diagnosis and attempted repair. It is not our job to be service technicians. If I had not complained, diagnosis and attempted repair was going to continue. Once you agreed to the swap everything went great. It was sent immediately, took almost no time for us to set up the instrument and we were immediately back in business. That should have taken a couple of days not a week or more.

QuestionDesc: One Message to Share Regarding Experience
ResultText: My name is Jessica Belton and I am the primary operator of our LC system at the Eastern lab of the VA Department of Forensic Science in the Controlled Substances Section (Norfolk, VA). First, I want to say how helpful and appreciative I have been of Mr. Craig Alberg. This was my first interaction with him and although brief, he has been the most helpful and respective representative of Agilent I have interacted with in the past two-three months. Originally, my coworker Roxanne Durning was the primary operator until this year when I took over. I asked Ms. Durning back in September regarding scheduling up our annual PM since it was due in October. She explained Agilent always reached out to her to set up the PM in the past and was surprised herself about the delay but assumed the process would be the same. In October (10/7), after not hearing from Agilent, I reached out to Dillon Torppey who has been our previous service engineer in the past for this instrument. After checking (10/11), he said Agilent had the wrong email address for Ms. Durning which is why we have not been contacted about scheduling.  Regardless, November 22nd was selected with Ms. Karen Kaikkonen scheduled as the field agent. I reached out to Ms. Kaikkonen prior to the scheduled date (11/18) to verify we were on the schedule. She never responded to my email.On November 22nd, I called her cell and she claimed she was never scheduled for the PM for the Eastern lab nor did she receive my previous email. After speaking with her on the phone and trying to determine where the miscommunication was, she eventually found my email and the Agilent confirmation email. She told me she could not make the service date due to having several appointments in the Central VA area. She emailed her supervisor (Peggy) and the scheduling coordinator (Adrienne Happi) to reschedule us for as soon as possible. December 1st was chosen with Mr. Alberg as the service engineer.I completely understand Mr. Alberg was unavailable for 12/1 due to a repair taking longer than anticipated 3-4 hours away and he admirably tried his best to remediate the situation. We were rescheduled for December 6th and Mr. Alberg arrived on time, was very professional during his time here and performed the PM in a respectable time.From my view point, I do not see how Eastern DFS is at fault for a PM being pushed for two months.  Mr. Alberg has come across as apologetic for the situation and actively trying to remediate the situation. To be clear, when Ms. Kaikkonen originally claimed she did not receive my email nor the scheduling confirmation only to later find them in her inbox, that definitely did not sit well. Regardless if it was honest or not, for her to have been scheduled for, I believe she said 4, appointments in Central VA when we are located in Norfolk obviously doesn't make sense logistically. So perhaps that is on the scheduling coordinator Adienne Hoppi. Honestly, deciphering that is not my responsibility. One last note of "incorrect contact information", Mr. Alberg mentioned an incorrect address for us. This was the first time someone mentioned an incorrect address as a reason for miscommunication. Again, we find this extremely hard to believe as a reason considering previous years and PMs on this/other instruments, let alone installs, have never had this occur. So, we do not see the validity of the statement "incorrect contact information" regarding email or address and the scheduling issues that have occurred. Mr. Alberg assured me the correct email/contact information and address have been corrected on our account. Mr. Alberg did forward his direct supervisor's contact information to me (Eric Hixson). I did reach out to Mr. Hixson and he was very apologetic about the situation. To sum up, as you can obviously read, this has been a very long drawn out process for two months, becoming increasingly frustrating. I am very appreciative of Mr. Alberg and his professionalism. He appears to be a great employee and I look forward to working with him in the future.

QuestionDesc: Description of Concerns and Relevant Product/Service
ResultText: There has been many issue with the AVS 7. First there was a crack in the bubble injector. additionally there was a mechanical issue with the switching valve. finally that was replaced and solved the issues. the teflon to UHMW? rotor seal made only slight improvements in my opinion; but was appreciated nonetheless. My experience with the multiple failures with the AVS valve itself has brought me to the conclusion that the three srews on the front of the valve body are tightened too much on install/service by the Agilent service reps. for example terrible grinding sounds are noted after service. I always loosen the three screws off enough to prevent this sound. I dont tighten enough to close the spacer gap. much better performance and less wear on valve seal and motor this way. I'm curious if others share my experience.

QuestionDesc: Description of Concerns and Relevant Product/Service
ResultText: Análisis de dietanolamina en cosméticos por GC-MS (por ejemplo, de acuerdo a ISO/TR 18818:2017). Posibles columnas a emplear. Posibilidad de emplear la actualmente instalada en nuestro GC-MS de Agilent para realizar esta aplicación de manera puntual: 19091S-433UI J&W HP-5ms Ultra Inert GC Column, 30 m, 0.25 mm, 0.25 µm, 7 inch cage.Quisiera poder comentar esta y otras dudas que pudieran surgir en el futuro con alguien. El anterior técnico de aplicaciones que nos atendía (Carlos Bueno) ya no está en su empresa, pero con él podía tener contacto al menos por correo electrónico y a veces por teléfono para resolver algunas dudas de vez en cuando, pero ahora parece que no es posible hablar con nadie.La experiencia habitual con otras empresas de instrumentación de las que tenemos equipos (Perkin Elmer, Metrohm, etc.) es que si hay alguna cuestión técnica, inicialmente la atiende el servicio de atención al cliente, pero dejan nota y luego nos llama algún técnico para resolver el problema o la duda, puesto que la comunicación es más fácil y fluida si se puede hablar con alguien y la cuestión se resuelve o al menos se trata de manera mucho más rápida.
ResultTextPred: Analysis of diethanolamine in cosmetics by GC-MS (e.g. according to ISO/TR 18818:2017). Possible columns to use. Possibility of using the one currently installed in our Agilent GC-MS to carry out this application on a specific basis: 19091S-433UI J&W HP-5ms Ultra Inert GC Column, 30 m, 0.25 mm, 0.25 µm, 7 inch cage. I would like to be able to comment on this and other doubts that may arise in the future with someone. The previous applications technician who assisted us (Carlos Bueno) is no longer in his company, but I could have contact with him at least by email and sometimes by phone to resolve some doubts from time to time, but now it seems that it is not possible talk to anyone. The usual experience with other instrumentation companies from which we have equipment (Perkin Elmer, Metrohm, etc.) is that if there is a technical issue, it is initially attended to by customer service, but they leave a note and then we Call a technician to resolve the problem or question, since communication is easier and more fluid if you can talk to someone and the issue is resolved or at least dealt with much more quickly.

QuestionDesc: One Message to Share Regarding Experience
ResultText: Agilent knows about the issues related to my Cary 6000i - they should be proactive in replacing this defective part.  Instead, they waited until it broke and I contacted them.  And then even after I contacted them, I was told it was probably a lamp issue.  This wasted at least two weeks while I ordered and then waited for two new lamps to arrive.  Then when I contacted Agilent again, I was told it was an alignment issue.  He had me run tests. Then more tests over the next two or three days.  All this was wasted time.  I finally asked for a service call - and Tom Smith came within two days.  This was the only good part of this entire process.  He was here on a Wednesday and said he'd get back with me regarding the new monochromator - he had to get it approved by Agilent.  I was still waiting on Monday of the following week and I had to email everyone at Agilent.  Tom called me on Tuesday saying it would be "two to three weeks" because the part had to be shipped from Malaysia.  What??!?!??  My instrument had already been down for "two to three weeks."  I protested and was told I had been moved to higher priority and that it would ship as soon as possible.  Over a week later, I got a call from a FedEx rep regarding the customs.  She said it would be another week before I got it.  It was here on a Monday (two weeks after getting the call from Tom) and then when I inquired about the installation date, I was told it would be the following week on Tuesday.  That would be the 23rd.  So, it was a total of three weeks from when Tom called me.  Had I not protested and been given higher priority, there's no telling how long it would have taken to get my instrument repaired. Agilent should contact all owners of spectrometers that contain this bad monochromator and proactively replace it.  At the very least, Agilent should have an inventory of the monochromator somewhere in the U.S.

Ainda assim, apesar de estar no geral satisfeito com o resultado do atendimento, não posso deixar de sentir preocupação em relação à esse detalhe.
ResultTextPred: Firstly, the service was excellent. They scheduled the service with the greatest agility, even though it did not completely meet my urgency, I understand that this is not something I could demand from Agilent. What left me dissatisfied with the experience was the issue of repeating the problem. Field service was carried out twice on the same day due to the breakage of the same part that had been replaced, and the next time the machine was used the problem reoccurred. The exchange was then made by us and the problem was resolved. If the problem was actually in the installation of the part, I am dissatisfied with the fact that the technician installed the part twice in a way that would result in the equipment stopping, and during the second installation he himself noticed that he could have installed the part in a improperly and still repeated the error. Of course, this could not be the problem, it could be defective parts or something like that. Still, despite being generally satisfied with the outcome of the service, I can't help but feel concerned about this detail.

QuestionDesc: One Message to Share Regarding Experience
ResultText: Die Lösung des Problems war letzlich eine defektes Tip Seal der Vorpumpe, welches bei der von Ihnen durchgeführten Jahreswartung nicht ausgetauscht wurde. Das Problem konnte von einem unserer Mitarbeiter durch eine kurze Messung des Vorpumpenvakuums innerhalb von 20 Minuten gefunden werden. Auf Nachfrage beim Techniker, der die Dichtung danach austauschte, warum das Problem nicht bei einem der zwei vorherigen Technikereinsätze  gefunden werden konnte, bekamen wir die Antwort, dass keine Möglichkeit bestünde das Vorpumpenvakuum zu messen, da keine Manometer mitgeführt werden. Die Vorgehensweise auf Verdacht hin Teile am Gerät auszutauschen, ohne einen vorherigen Versuch das Problem einzugrenzen ist ineffizient, kostenspielig und frustrierend.Wir hätten uns dahingehend eine bessere Problemdiagnostik durch die Techniker und mehr Möglichkeiten zur Fehlersuche am Gerät selbst gewünscht.
ResultTextPred: The solution to the problem was ultimately a defective tip seal on the backing pump, which was not replaced during the annual maintenance you carried out. One of our employees was able to find the problem within 20 minutes by briefly measuring the backing pump vacuum. When we asked the technician who replaced the seal why the problem could not be found during one of the two previous technician visits, we were told that there was no way to measure the forepump vacuum because no pressure gauges were carried. The procedure of replacing parts of the device on suspicion without first trying to isolate the problem is inefficient, expensive and frustrating. We would have liked better problem diagnosis by the technicians and more options for troubleshooting the device itself.

ResultText: Agilent`s website needs to be overhauled. Sometimes manuals are present, sometimes not. It is very difficult to find parts for chromatography (connectors, tubing). Half of the manuals (for almost all liquid chromatography products) consist of pictures how to drain the system (tubings installation for leakage cases) and advertising the agilent plastic bottle at the end. Technically this is very unimportant information and almost self explanatory. Unless organic solvents are used just about any vessel does this job. The manuals leave me always with a feeling that only a fraction of the instruments capabilities is thoroughly described. Software sections are also not good. Possibilities for changing settings (just to rename a valve) are awkward and often require an engineer. The quality and durability of your HPLC pumps stands in contrast to the descriptions on running them. One needs time to adapt to the non-intuitive control in ChemStation, but after adapting to the way, an Agilent HPLC performs in our hands very reliably. The ADL hooks for the Eclipse Fluorometer should be available as a download and this should also be clearly indicated with a link. Unfortunately this instrument is standing really in the shadow of the HPLC family. A renewed and more straightforward software control without opening individual applications is definitely something that should be done.

QuestionDesc: Q05_xother
ResultText: I was getting an error message (UV strike failure) on Cary 300 bio instrument. I placed an order for new UV lamp and tried replacing it. I have replaced the UV lamp in the past on numerous occasions. However, I was told that while replacing the UV lamp I should be cautious that I do not push the lamp all the way down, so I used to be very careful while placing the UV lamp. This time I again got the error message and after contacting with the technical team, I told them about the issue that I was facing. I was suggested that the Solenoid needs a replacement. When the technician arrived, he tried changing the power board but still was unable to get the instrument working. After almost an hour he realized that the UV lamp needs to be secured in place by tightening the Philip screws. He put back the old power board and the machine started working. The only thing machine needed was UV lamp replacement and making sure that Philip screws are made tight enough to push the lamp deeper enough than what I tried before. I feel that had I not been told to not push lamp all the way down and that this time I make sure that I push lamp to enough depth then my lab would have saved good amount of money. The online lamp alignment notes are not that helpful.
